{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d17d37de-1bc1-426b-a080-472d2688e448","content":"After a .NET SDK update, use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update, since workload manifests and packs may have changed.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads that are already installed but corrupted or partially installed. It doesn't upgrade anything — it just fixes broken installations.\n\n**TL;DR:** `dotnet workload update` aligns your workloads with the new SDK. Run `dotnet workload repair` only if the update itself fails or workloads appear corrupted.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c0bb1dfb-5aa6-410f-a43e-c7f9e3ed0396","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question that doesn't require tool usage - I can answer directly.","outputTokens":236,"requestId":"083B:18DC0C:9CD615:B6363D:69F2A770"},"id":"d87dd6ef-9571-4786-bb88-16f93a7ffebb","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:51:02.768Z","parentId":"95a12b40-e2fd-4496-9356-e3c569641588"}
